                <head>238. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On December 6, President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> and
                    his principal Cabinet officers briefed President-elect Kennedy on the most
                    significant world problems facing the United States. In a review of the danger
                    spots, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName> stated: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“<hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi>—This is acute and dangerous, and Mr.
                                <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> has heavy pressure
                            to get the Berlin question settled and to stop the movement of refugees
                            to the West from behind the Iron Curtain.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>A memorandum for the record of this meeting is in the <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName corresp="#p_WAC1"
                        >Whitman</persName> File, Presidential Transition Series.</p>
            </div>
